phase1.explanation:
Here are the most common Java exceptions you'll encounter:

--- 1. NullPointerException (Unchecked) ---

When: Trying to call a method on a null reference

String str = null;
str.length(); // NPE!

FIX: Always check for null:
if (str != null) {
    int len = str.length();
}

--- 2. ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException (Unchecked) ---

When: Accessing an array index outside 0 to length-1

int[] arr = {1, 2, 3};
arr[5] = 10; // Index 5 out of bounds!

FIX: Check index bounds:
if (index >= 0 && index < arr.length) {
    arr[index] = value;
}

--- 3. ClassCastException (Unchecked) ---

When: Invalid downcasting

Animal animal = new Dog();
Cat cat = (Cat) animal; // Dog can't be cast to Cat!

FIX: Use instanceof before casting:
if (animal instanceof Cat) {
    Cat cat = (Cat) animal;
}

--- 4. NumberFormatException (Unchecked) ---

When: Converting invalid string to number

int num = Integer.parseInt("123abc"); // "123abc" not a valid number!

FIX: Try-catch or validate input:
try {
    int num = Integer.parseInt(input);
} catch (NumberFormatException e) {
    System.out.println("Invalid number format!");
}

--- 5. ArithmeticException (Unchecked) ---

When: Math error (division by zero)

int result = 100 / 0; // division by zero!

FIX: Check divisor before division:
if (divisor != 0) {
    int result = 100 / divisor;
}

--- 6. IllegalArgumentException (Unchecked) ---

When: Invalid argument passed to method

setAge(-5); // age can't be negative!

FIX: Validate before using:
if (age < 0) {
    throw new IllegalArgumentException("Age can't be negative!");
}

--- 7. IndexOutOfBoundsException (Unchecked) ---

When: Invalid index for list/array

ArrayList<String> list = new ArrayList<>();
list.get(5); // Index 5 out of bounds!

FIX: Check size():
if (index >= 0 && index < list.size()) {
    String item = list.get(index);
}

--- 8. FileNotFoundException (Checked) ---

When: File doesn't exist

new FileReader("missing.txt"); // File not found!

FIX: Try-catch or check if file exists:
File file = new File("missing.txt");
if (file.exists()) {
    FileReader reader = new FileReader(file);
}

--- 9. IOException (Checked) ---

When: I/O operation fails

reader.read(); // I/O error!

FIX: Try-catch with proper error handling:
try {
    reader.read();
} catch (IOException e) {
    System.out.println("I/O Error: " + e.getMessage());
}

--- 10. InterruptedException (Checked) ---

When: Thread is interrupted while sleeping/waiting

Thread.sleep(1000); // might be interrupted!

FIX: Try-catch:
try {
    Thread.sleep(1000);
} catch (InterruptedException e) {
    Thread.currentThread().interrupt(); // restore status
}

Remember:
• Unchecked exceptions = programming errors (fix the code)
• Checked exceptions = external problems (handle gracefully)
